  "What is the 'damping factor' in Google's PageRank and how does it affect eigenvalues?": "",
  "A factor that increases all eigenvalues by 15%": "",
  "A parameter that controls the number of eigenvalues computed": "",
  "A multiplier applied to the page content score": "",
  "A value d (typically 0.85) that ensures the modified matrix has a unique dominant eigenvalue of 1": "",
  "The damping factor d blends the link matrix with a uniform matrix: M' = dM + (1-d)(1/n)ee^T. This guarantees all secondary eigenvalues have |lambda| <= d < 1, ensuring unique convergence.": "",
  "What does 'low-rank approximation' mean in the context of eigenvalues?": "",
  "Removing rows and columns to make the matrix smaller": "",
  "Making all eigenvalues equal": "",
  "Reducing the matrix to its smallest eigenvalue only": "",
  "Approximating a matrix by keeping only the terms corresponding to the k largest eigenvalues": "",
  "Low-rank approximation A_k = sum of lambda_i v_i v_i^T for i = 1,...,k retains the k largest eigenvalue/eigenvector pairs. The Eckart-Young theorem says this is the best rank-k approximation.": "",
  "What is 'convergence rate' of an iterative method in terms of eigenvalues?": "",
  "The number of eigenvalues that are zero": "",
  "The rate is determined by the spectral radius; smaller spectral radius means faster convergence": "",
  "The convergence rate equals the trace of the iteration matrix": "",
  "The largest eigenvalue determines how many iterations are needed": "",
  "The error after k iterations decays approximately as rho(B)^k, where rho(B) is the spectral radius of the iteration matrix. Smaller rho means faster convergence.": "",
